{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535851"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:00:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:00:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15551"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15551"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.14,0.22,0.09,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8242"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106264"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8242"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88732"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3191"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4038"},{"type":"tags","id":"9121"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28724"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106264"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old man is admitted to the Palliative Care ward with metastatic colorectal cancer for management of nausea and vomiting. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His current medications include a subcutaneous syringe driver containing morphine and haloperidol for symptom control. His nausea has improved since admission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver the past 24 hours, he has become increasingly confused and agitated. He is pulling at his clothes, trying to get out of bed, and having difficulty following conversations. His family are distressed by these changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears restless with a fluctuating level of consciousness. His vital signs show a pulse rate of 98/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence midazolam in syringe driver","Add olanzapine wafer","Increase haloperidol dose","Commence oral lorazepam","Start regular quetiapine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with terminal delirium, which is common in the last days to weeks of life. The symptoms include acute confusion, agitation, and altered consciousness. Given that he is already receiving first-line treatment with haloperidol without adequate symptom control, escalation of therapy is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMidazolam\u003C/strong\u003E in a syringe driver is the most appropriate next step as it provides effective sedation that can be easily titrated. It has a rapid onset of action and can be delivered continuously via the existing syringe driver. The goal is to achieve the right balance between symptom control and maintaining some ability to communicate with family.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlanzapine\u003C/strong\u003E wafer, while easier to administer than tablets, would not be the most appropriate choice when rapid symptom control is needed. As an antipsychotic, it may take several days to achieve optimal effect, and the patient is already receiving haloperidol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing haloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E dose alone may not provide adequate symptom control and could increase the risk of extrapyramidal side effects. When terminal delirium is not responding to standard doses, adding a benzodiazepine is often more effective than increasing the antipsychotic dose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral lorazepam\u003C/strong\u003E would be difficult to administer reliably in an agitated patient. While benzodiazepines are appropriate, the subcutaneous route is preferred in this setting for reliable drug delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuetiapine\u003C/strong\u003E is an atypical antipsychotic that can be useful in delirium but would not be the best choice when more rapid control of symptoms is needed. Additionally, oral medications may be difficult to administer reliably at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of terminal delirium requires careful consideration of the balance between symptom control and maintaining some degree of communication with family. Non-pharmacological measures such as family presence, reorientation, and maintaining day-night cycles should continue alongside pharmacological management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Terminal delirium requires a balanced approach between symptom control and maintaining communication with family in the last days of life.","Haloperidol is the first-line antipsychotic for managing terminal delirium.","Non-pharmacological measures such as reorientation and family presence are important but may be insufficient in terminal delirium."],"references":["Bush SH, Tierney S, Lawlor PG. Clinical Assessment and Management of Delirium in the Palliative Care Setting. Drugs. 2017 Oct;77(15):1623-1643. doi: 10.1007/s40265-017-0804-3. PMID: 28864877; PMCID: PMC5613058. Available online at ; https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5613058/#CR87"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88732"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15551"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88732"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-17T15:21:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T15:21:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8242"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106264"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGro